defaultQ284default              defaultChair:default May I welcome our two distinguished witnesses to this session of the Public Administration Select Committee on crime statistics, and particularly recorded crime statistics in the Metropolitan Police?  Can I ask each of you to identify yourselves for the record, please?
default              defaultSir Bernard Hogan-Howedefault: Good morning, Chairman.  My name is Bernard Hogan-Howe, the Commissioner of the Metropolitan Police.
default              defaultStephen defaultGreenhalghdefault: Stephen 
defaultGreenhalgh
default, Deputy Mayor for Policing and Crime.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ285default              default defaultChair:default Thank you for coming to us today.  Can I also invite you to give short and sharp answers?  We will do our best to ask short and sharp questions, and I will pull up colleagues—and I will pull you up—if things are getting a bit protracted.  If I may kick off, do we all accept that the general concern about the integrity of crime statistics is legitimate?
default              defaultSir Bernard Hogan-Howedefault: Yes, certainly for me, Chairman.  It is vital that we have crime statistics that we can trust.  I have said numerous times, following from your Committee meeting, that there are two big reasons why we need to have trust in our crime stats.  The first is for the benefit of the victim.  They need to make sure, obviously, that their crime is recorded accurately.  Secondly, it is really important that we know how much crime there is and whether it is going up or down, so that the police can take action.  Frankly at times, I suppose, the police and others want to take the benefit of reducing crime.  We can hardly take that benefit—that we did something that was good—if we have crime statistics 
defaultthat we cannot rely on.  For many reasons, it is vital that those crime statistics can be relied on.
default              defaultStephen defaultGreenhalghdefault: Absolutely.  It is the reason why, back in March 2013, I asked a body that is independent of both the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime and the Metropolitan Police Service to look into the integrity of crime recording.  It has looked at the systems and processes, and its report will be available at the end of this month.  It is a legitimate concern.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ286default              defaultChair:default Sir Bernard, when PC James Patrick appeared before us, we found his evidence quite compelling, and you responded saying you would like to get to the bottom of this and find out what he is alleging and how widespread it is, and talk to Mr Patrick about his concerns.  Have you done so?
default              defaultSir Bernard Hogan-Howedefault: What we have done up to now is that, first of all, what I said was I want an inquiry into his concerns.  One of the things we had to watch is that, first of all, we were approaching the Christmas period, but probably more importantly
default—
defaultas you are aware
default—
defaultwe were actually asked by this Committee, when we approached him about his welfare, whether we were
default trying to interfere with his evidence to this Committee.  For that reason, we have been a little careful about approaching him directly.  You are also aware
default—
defaultI think it has been put in the public domain by this officer and this Committee
default—
defaultthat there is a misconduct process around him.  So for various reasons, we have not approached him directly about that inquiry, but we will within a short period of time.  However, we have started an inquiry internally, led by the Deputy Commissioner, to look at his claims, of which we have made some assessment.  Obviously, what will be really helpful is when we can talk to him directly.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ287default              defaultChair:default When will you speak to Mr Patrick?
default              defaultSir Bernard Hogan-Howedefault: I would expect within 
defaultthe next few weeks.  As I said, we were a little compromised by the fact that, as you know, the Clerk to this Committee asked us why we were approaching him after his appearance at the Committee
default, and whether we were trying to interfere with his objectivity
default, which we were not; we were checking on his welfare.  We did have to take some cognisance of that before we approached him, but we have 
defaultnot been idle in that time.  I think
default there were 
default20 claims in the papers we initially received.  We have made some assessment of those 20 claims.
