defaultQ329default              defaultAlun Cairns:default How confident are you in the accuracy of the data on serious and sexual offences?
default              defaultSir Bernard Hogan-Howedefault: I think it is a lot better than it was, if we took it back five to 10 years, but I am not yet sure that we can entirely rely on it.  As you will probably be aware, there are all sorts of complexities, and I have decided
default—
defaultpartly on the back of this report
default, but because of some other issues of well
default—
defaultto do two or three things to establish whether we should be entirely content with where we are.  
defaultThe main issue about sexual offences, as you obviously understand, is the issue of consent.  That is usually the issue, whether it be rape or 
defaultany other sexual offence, and that is quite a problem to establish.  Sometimes people later claim either no consent or change their mind about consent.  Occasionally, people go back into relationships with the person who attacked them.  
defaultFor many reasons, it is quite a complex area.  We already know that around 80% to 85% of victims of sexual offence do not even bother reporting it, so we have a huge unreported amount of crime.  For lots of reasons, it is a complex area.  You might have seen in the 
defaultEvening Standard
