defaultQ462default              defaultDavid defaultHeyesdefault:default If your efforts succeed and there is much greater integrity in the stats, we will see an increase in the levels of recorded crime.  That is going to be, politically, extremely unpopular.  We are not innocent parties in this, as politicians.  It is very much the result of politicians of all parties over the years who have contributed to bringing about this culture.  How are you going to deal with the fact that your success in your endeavours is going to make you extremely politically unpopular, potentially, for example, with the Home Office?
default              defaultTom Winsordefault: It is not inevitable that improvements in the integrity of the recording of crime will lead to an increase in crime.  As AIC 
defaultPinkney
default said, it may be that we will find cases where more than one crime is recorded when in fact only one crime has been committed, but it is conceptually possible that it will show a rise for some crime categories.  For example, on sexual offences, particularly sexual offences against children, or many of the other under
default&#x2011;
defaultrecorded
default or under
default&#x2011;
defaultreported
default crimes, it would be a good thing.  If the police know these crimes are taking place, they can tackle them and deal with it.  
defaultThere is a lot of crime that is just not reported.  Examples include paedophilia, child sexual exploitation, human trafficking, cyber
default&#x2011;
defaultcrime
default, identity theft, counterfeiting, undetected drugs, gun trafficking, money laundering and internal corporate fraud.  A lot of these things are not recorded, and also the national crime recording standards do not include some things that everybody would regard as a crime, for example motoring offences.  The example given to me by the Chief Constable of Derbyshire, Mr 
defaultCreedon
default, is the uninsured drunk driver in an un
default&#x2011;
defaultroadworthy
default car speeding in a built
default&#x2011;
defaultup area and speaking on his mobile phone.  That is not recorded as a crime, according to the national crime recording standards, but shoplifting a piece of chewing gum from a multinational supermarket counts as a crime.  The data only tells you a certain amount, not the whole picture.  
defaultYou mentioned, if we do conclude that there is more crime than has presently been recorded, that this would lead to a political dissatisfaction.  As I mentioned in response to an earlier question, we do not operate according to political criteria.  There are no political criteria in the Police Act 1996.  We will not operate according to any political criteria; they would be irrelevant considerations in any of our reports, and we would be correctly successfully judicially reviewed if we allowed political considerations to enter into them.
